Transmissible spongiform encephalopathies
(TSE)1 are uniformly fatal
neurodegenerative diseases that include variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease in humans, scrapie in sheep, chronic wasting disease in deer
and elk, and bovine spongiform encephalopathy. The nature of the
infectious agent is still controversial (1-3). A key event during TSE
pathogenesis is the conversion of the normal host protein, PrP-sen, to
an abnormal disease-associated form, PrP-res
